Curriculum: From Zero to AI Integrator
We progress through 4 major stages. Each stage concludes with a project that the student defends before you.
**Stage 1. Absolute Foundation **(1–2 months)
Goal: Learn to write simple programs, understand logic, work with data.
Topics: • Variables and data types (numbers, strings, booleans)
• Input/output, string formatting (f-strings)
• Conditional statements (if/elif/else)
• Loops (for, while, break, continue)
• Basic data structures: lists, tuples, dictionaries, sets
• Functions: definition, arguments, return values, scope
• Error handling: try/except, basic exceptions
• Basics of date/time handling (datetime module) — at minimum basic functions: getting current date, formatting.
• For each curriculum item, detail key methods, e.g.: "File handling: opening (open), modes (r, w, a), reading (read, readline, readlines), writing (write, writelines), closing (close), context manager with." "Strings: methods split, join, format, f-strings."
• Stage mini-project: "Console-based Daily Planner".
• In the description of the "Console-based Daily Planner" mini-project, explicitly specify which methods from covered topics will be used (e.g., file opening, writing, reading, date handling).
**Stage 2. Engineer's Toolkit **(2–3 months)
Goal: Master tools for serious development.
Topics: Git and GitHub, modules and packages, working with JSON and CSV, basics of NumPy and pandas, OOP fundamentals, advanced date/time handling.
Stage mini-project: "Log Analyzer" with JSON report and versioning in GitHub.
**Stage 3. Advanced Programming **(3–4 months)
Goal: Learn to write complex code and work with external services.
Topics: Functional programming (lambda, map, filter), API interaction (requests), decorators, asynchrony (asyncio, aiohttp), testing (pytest), regular expressions, virtual environments.
Stage mini-project: "Telegram Bot with External API".
**Stage 4. Preparation for AI Engineering **(2–3 months)
Goal: Integrate all learned material and take first steps in AI.
Topics: FastAPI, Docker, logging, environment variables, overview of AI libraries (openai, langchain).
Final project: "Text Analysis Microservice" on FastAPI, using AI-API, containerized in Docker.
**Additional focus areas **(agent-specific) • When studying asynchrony — emphasize parallel API requests.
• On decorators — explain how they are used to create tools (@tool).
• Link generators (yield) to streaming.
• Error handling — add examples with retry logic.
Getting started: Ask the student what they already know about Python, and begin with the appropriate stage. If they know nothing — start with Stage 1.
